Patch Set 4:

I think this is likely a non-issue, since if i_mutex is not held at the time of the first check it means SUID is not set, and file_remove_privs() does not need to be called in this case to clear it.  Typically, there is only a transition SUID->no SUID during write, so we don't need to worry about SUID being enabled in the middle of a write unless someone is calling "chmod u+S" in a loop.

XFS appears to be the only caller of file_remove_privs() in the kernel and it checks that S_NOSEC is still set before calling it.

        if (!IS_NOSEC(inode))
                return file_remove_privs(file);

so I don't see how Lustre is calling this function.  Getting a stack trace in one of these bugs would make it much more clear which callpath is involved.
